Analysis of Dental Magic’s Human Resources Dataset

Jennie Eardley

08/10/2020

Data Source

This is a dataset based around a fictional company called Dental Magic, created to teach HR analytics. The dataset is from Kaggle and is available here: https://www.kaggle.com/rhuebner/human-resources-data-set

The most common recruitment route is via a diversity job fair, with search engines closely following. Other targeted methods of recruitment seem to be less successful, particularly on campus recruiting, web banner ads and information sessions. It may be worth considering funds spent on these activities and their content.

Diversity

Performance This graph shows the overall picture of performance within the company. While it does include those who have left, it excludes those who are listed but have not yet started. They seem to have erroneously been assigned a performance category and removing them prevents inaccuracies in performance score reporting.

The vast majority of employees’ performance is rated as “fully meets” (78%). 12% of employees have a score of exceeds and 6% and 4% have scores of needs improvement and pip respectively.

satisfaction_by_position <- hr %>% 
  group_by(position) %>% 
  summarise(average_score = round(mean(emp_satisfaction), digits = 2))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
position_count <- hr %>% 
  count(position)

position_satsifaction <- full_join(satisfaction_by_position, position_count) %>% 
  rename("number_of_employees" = "n") %>% 
  filter(number_of_employees > 1) %>% 
  arrange(desc(average_score))

Employee Satisfaction Levels

Employee satisfaction is measured on a scale of 1-5, with 5 indicating the highest satisfaction. Across the dataset, the median scoring for employee satisfaction is 4. It is notable that while employees with the highest performance level of “exceeds” is the only category where the mode is 5, they do not seem to be significantly more satisfied than those with other performance levels. It is unsuprising that employees with the “needs improvement” and “pip” performance levels have disproportionately incidence of a satisfaction level of 2 and two people have reported a satisfaction level of 1.

## [1] 4

Gender Pay Gap

On average, men earn $33.70 compared to $29.47 for women. On average, men earn more than women in nine different positions. The position with the highest discrepancy is IT support workers where men earn a mean of $38.66 compared to $32.18 for women. On average, women earn more than men in six different positions with the largest discrepancy being for software engineers where women earn an average of 52.33 compared to the 48.56 earned by men.
